  ('gate-core-cs-computer-networks-q02', 'gate-core-cs-computer-networks', 'The number of usable host addresses in a /24 IPv4 network is:', '254', '256', '255', '128', 'A', 'A /24 has 2 to the 8 addresses minus 2 reserved, giving 254 usable hosts.', 1),
  ('gate-core-cs-computer-networks-q03', 'gate-core-cs-computer-networks', 'Which protocol maps an IP address to a MAC address?', 'ARP', 'DNS', 'HTTP', 'ICMP', 'A', 'ARP resolves an IP address to its corresponding MAC address.', 2),
  ('gate-core-cs-computer-networks-q04', 'gate-core-cs-computer-networks', 'At which OSI layer does the IP protocol operate?', 'Transport', 'Network', 'Data link', 'Application', 'B', 'IP operates at the network layer, handling routing of packets.', 3),
  ('gate-core-cs-computer-networks-q05', 'gate-core-cs-computer-networks', 'The data unit at the data link layer is called a:', 'Segment', 'Packet', 'Frame', 'Bit', 'C', 'The data link layer encapsulates data into frames.', 4),
  ('gate-core-cs-computer-networks-q06', 'gate-core-cs-computer-networks', 'Which protocol resolves human-readable domain names to IP addresses?', 'TCP', 'DNS', 'ARP', 'FTP', 'B', 'DNS translates domain names into IP addresses.', 5),
  ('gate-core-cs-computer-networks-q07', 'gate-core-cs-computer-networks', 'TCP achieves flow control primarily through:', 'Subnet masks', 'Broadcast storms', 'A sliding window', 'MAC filtering', 'C', 'TCP uses a sliding window to control how much unacknowledged data is in flight.', 6),
  ('gate-core-cs-computer-networks-q08', 'gate-core-cs-computer-networks', 'Compared to TCP, UDP is:', 'Connection-oriented and reliable', 'A network-layer protocol', 'Always encrypted', 'Connectionless and faster', 'D', 'UDP is connectionless with low overhead, trading reliability for speed.', 7),
  ('gate-core-cs-theory-of-computation-q01', 'gate-core-cs-theory-of-computation', 'Which machine recognizes exactly the class of regular languages?', 'Finite automaton', 'Turing machine', 'Pushdown automaton', 'Linear bounded automaton', 'A', 'Finite automata, both DFA and NFA, recognize exactly the regular languages.', 0),
  ('gate-core-cs-theory-of-computation-q02', 'gate-core-cs-theory-of-computation', 'The language a raised to n followed by b raised to n is:', 'Regular', 'Finite', 'Context-free but not regular', 'Not a language', 'C', 'Matching counts of a and b is context-free, but the pumping lemma shows it is not regular.', 1),
  ('gate-core-cs-theory-of-computation-q03', 'gate-core-cs-theory-of-computation', 'A pushdown automaton differs from a finite automaton by having a:', 'Queue', 'Two-way tape', 'Stack', 'Random-access memory', 'C', 'A PDA augments a finite automaton with a stack to recognize context-free languages.', 2),
  ('gate-core-cs-theory-of-computation-q04', 'gate-core-cs-theory-of-computation', 'The pumping lemma is most commonly used to prove that a language is:', 'Not regular', 'Decidable', 'Context-free', 'Finite', 'A', 'The pumping lemma provides a contradiction tool to show non-regularity.', 3),
  ('gate-core-cs-theory-of-computation-q05', 'gate-core-cs-theory-of-computation', 'A deterministic finite automaton and a nondeterministic finite automaton:', 'Recognize different language classes', 'Both require a stack', 'Recognize the same class of languages', 'Cannot be converted to each other', 'C', 'Every NFA has an equivalent DFA, so both accept exactly the regular languages.', 4),
  ('gate-core-cs-theory-of-computation-q06', 'gate-core-cs-theory-of-computation', 'The Halting Problem is an example of a problem that is:', 'Decidable', 'Regular', 'Undecidable', 'Context-free', 'C', 'The Halting Problem is undecidable; no algorithm decides it for all inputs.', 5),
  ('gate-core-cs-theory-of-computation-q07', 'gate-core-cs-theory-of-computation', 'Recursively enumerable languages are recognized by a:', 'Turing machine', 'Pushdown automaton', 'Finite automaton', 'Regular expression', 'A', 'Turing machines recognize the recursively enumerable languages.', 6),
  ('gate-core-cs-theory-of-computation-q08', 'gate-core-cs-theory-of-computation', 'Context-free languages are generated by a:', 'Context-free grammar', 'Regular expression', 'Finite automaton', 'Truth table', 'A', 'A context-free grammar generates exactly the context-free languages.', 7),
  ('gate-core-cs-compiler-design-q01', 'gate-core-cs-compiler-design', 'Which compiler phase produces tokens from the source program?', 'Syntax analysis', 'Code generation', 'Lexical analysis', 'Semantic analysis', 'C', 'Lexical analysis scans characters and emits tokens.', 0),
  ('gate-core-cs-compiler-design-q02', 'gate-core-cs-compiler-design', 'An LL(1) parser performs which type of parsing?', 'Bottom-up', 'Right-to-left', 'Random', 'Top-down with one lookahead', 'D', 'LL(1) is top-down, reading left-to-right with one symbol of lookahead.', 1),
  ('gate-core-cs-compiler-design-q03', 'gate-core-cs-compiler-design', 'The output of the syntax analysis phase is typically a:', 'Parse tree', 'Symbol table only', 'Token stream', 'Machine code', 'A', 'Syntax analysis builds a parse tree reflecting the grammar structure.', 2),
  ('gate-core-cs-compiler-design-q04', 'gate-core-cs-compiler-design', 'Before LL(1) parsing, a grammar must typically be free of:', 'Terminals', 'Start symbols', 'Left recursion', 'Productions', 'C', 'LL(1) parsing requires removing left recursion, often with left factoring too.', 3),
